1
00:00:00,537 --> 00:00:18,917
Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa Namo tassa bhagavato hara-hatto samma-sambuddhassa

2
00:00:18,896 --> 00:00:48,549
Namo Tassa Bhagavato Arahato Samma Sambuddhasa homage to the blessed, noble and fully self-enlightened one so we're following this compilation by Bhikkhu Bodhi and we've been through the heavy bit sickness, aging and death so we're still unfortunately on the heaviness of life

3
00:00:49,340 --> 00:01:18,468
the joys come at the end and here the Buddha is now going into what you might call the basic psychology of how we create suffering for ourselves and he uses the word worldling an uninstructed worldling as though looking at the world as if we were aliens but he's just trying to translate a word which just means an ordinary person who doesn't know

4
00:01:18,736 --> 00:01:20,177
why they cause themselves suffering.

5
00:01:20,277 --> 00:01:22,540
It doesn't come across the Buddha's teaching.

6
00:01:27,745 --> 00:01:29,186
Yeah, that's the only word.

7
00:01:29,225 --> 00:01:32,108
I think you might wonder what he means by it.

8
00:01:32,709 --> 00:01:39,495
So, monks, and remember that these discourses always begin with monks, but it stands for anybody who's listening, really.

9
00:01:40,777 --> 00:01:45,081
When the uninstructed worldling experiences a painful feeling,

10
00:01:46,411 --> 00:01:48,552
he sorrows, grieves and laments.

11
00:01:49,134 --> 00:01:51,977
He weeps, beating his breath and becomes distraught.

12
00:01:52,778 --> 00:01:56,402
He feels two feelings, a bodily one and a mental one.

13
00:01:57,783 --> 00:02:08,715
Now suppose they were to strike a man with a dart and then strike him immediately afterwards with a second dart, so that the man would feel a feeling caused by two darts.

14
00:02:09,536 --> 00:02:15,641
So too, when the uninstructed worldly experiences a painful feeling, he feels two feelings,

15
00:02:15,925 --> 00:02:17,986
a bodily one and a mental one.

16
00:02:19,949 --> 00:02:25,033
While experiencing that same painful feeling, she harbors aversion towards it.

17
00:02:26,014 --> 00:02:38,586
When she harbors aversion towards painful feeling, the underlying tendency to aversion towards painful feeling lies behind this.

18
00:02:39,788 --> 00:02:44,953
And while experiencing painful feeling, she seeks delight in sensual pleasure.

19
00:02:45,658 --> 00:02:46,479
For what reason?

20
00:02:47,140 --> 00:02:55,088
Because the uninstructed worldling does not know of any escape from painful feeling other than sensual pleasure.

21
00:02:56,471 --> 00:03:05,080
And when she seeks delight in sensual pleasure, the underlying tendency of lust for pleasant feeling lies behind this.

22
00:03:06,100 --> 00:03:10,806
She does not understand as it really is the origin and the passing away

23
00:03:11,191 --> 00:03:16,237
the gratification, the danger and the escape in case of these feelings.

24
00:03:17,379 --> 00:03:27,713
When she does not understand these feelings the underlying tendency to ignorance in regard to neither painful nor pleasant feeling lies behind this.

25
00:03:32,901 --> 00:03:36,967
If they feel a pleasant feeling they feel it attached.

26
00:03:38,528 --> 00:03:40,472
And if they feel a painful feeling

27
00:03:40,823 --> 00:03:42,064
they feel it attached.

28
00:03:43,086 --> 00:03:47,432
And if they feel a neither painful nor pleasant feeling, they feel it attached.

29
00:03:48,534 --> 00:04:02,556
This is called an uninstructed worldling who is attached to birth, aging, and death, who is attached to sorrow, lamentation, pain, dejection, and despair, who is attached to suffering, I say.

30
00:04:04,680 --> 00:04:05,842
So there's a lot of meat in this.

31
00:04:05,921 --> 00:04:07,084
Books are written on this, you know.

32
00:04:07,789 --> 00:04:15,122
I myself have a wonderful talk, which you can download from the website, on the gratification, the danger and the escape.

33
00:04:15,742 --> 00:04:16,805
So, what's the Buddha saying?

34
00:04:17,346 --> 00:04:34,353
He's saying, first of all, when we feel something harmful, when we feel something painful in the body, now remember there's two types of feelings in the body, those feelings that come from the body itself, such as, you know, I know painful knees when you're sitting,

35
00:04:34,925 --> 00:04:41,696
And those painful feelings that are in the body coming from the heart, our emotional states.

36
00:04:41,716 --> 00:04:45,041
Now, that's bad enough to be able to sit with that.

37
00:04:45,201 --> 00:04:51,774
But then we have this second dart, as he calls it, which is the resistance, not wanting to go there.

38
00:04:52,956 --> 00:04:58,184
So we have both the painful feeling and now we've created an aversion to it.

39
00:04:59,786 --> 00:05:00,949
So now we're in turmoil.

40
00:05:02,144 --> 00:05:31,071
because we're in turmoil we're now seeking an escape okay and the escape is tea and biscuits basically turn on the TV phone up a friend do anything apart from feel these feelings right that's the gratification but unfortunately you see if we go on we don't see the danger of that because when we're gratified because when we're enjoying ourselves

41
00:05:31,507 --> 00:05:32,288
It's okay.

42
00:05:32,507 --> 00:05:33,288
I mean, we're in heaven.

43
00:05:33,329 --> 00:05:34,029
What's the problem?

44
00:05:34,851 --> 00:05:43,202
We don't see the problems that arise after that, which is that we've suppressed these feelings and they're there within the system.

45
00:05:44,464 --> 00:05:46,367
We're not actually dealt with them.

46
00:05:46,387 --> 00:05:55,180
And secondly, when that pleasant feeling disappears, we find that we become attached to it.

47
00:05:55,199 --> 00:05:59,745
Attached here means psychologically dependent on something for our happiness.

48
00:06:01,247 --> 00:06:01,327
See?

49
00:06:01,696 --> 00:06:03,774
So there's a lot of psychology here.

50
00:06:04,041 --> 00:06:09,108
And if we go through it just bit by bit, then we'll see.

51
00:06:09,228 --> 00:06:14,853
So when an uninstructed worldly experiences a painful feeling, see, they immediately react to it.

52
00:06:15,274 --> 00:06:21,581
They're sorry about it, they grieve about it, they lament, they weep beating their breasts, becoming distraught, right?

53
00:06:22,081 --> 00:06:30,711
Now, just think of the time when you've been even a little bit ill and it stops you going to work or it stops you doing something, a bad cold, a flu, see?

54
00:06:31,112 --> 00:06:32,613
So there's that negativity, right?

55
00:06:32,593 --> 00:06:53,572
now that's the second dart what the Buddha is saying is that's not necessary so that's the second dart and what he points out is that therefore unless we are aware of that then we'll keep making things worse for ourselves by this reaction

56
00:06:56,252 --> 00:06:58,857
So he harbors aversion towards person.

57
00:06:58,877 --> 00:06:59,617
He harbors it.

58
00:06:59,677 --> 00:07:02,562
We develop that aversion towards painful feeling.

59
00:07:03,002 --> 00:07:05,146
So that means there's a lot of fear there too.

60
00:07:05,406 --> 00:07:13,958
So whatever we feel, whatever we think there's going to be a bit of difficulty for us, a bit of painfulness for us, we tend to run for it.

61
00:07:16,958 --> 00:07:36,860
And the aversion is, what is manifesting is an underlying tendency to aversion, which means that we already have a conditioning within us to either resist or run from what we find unpleasant.

62
00:07:38,262 --> 00:07:44,350
Every time we react like that, we reinforce this tendency, this conditioning, this habit within us.

63
00:07:44,785 --> 00:07:48,468
So we're actually making things worse all the time for ourselves.

64
00:07:53,113 --> 00:07:59,321
And because it gets so bad, while experiencing a pleasant feeling, they seek sensual pleasure.

65
00:08:00,663 --> 00:08:02,223
So that's what we do, isn't it?

66
00:08:02,764 --> 00:08:06,889
Things get a bit tough, so you get drunk.

67
00:08:06,910 --> 00:08:10,994
Anything not to feel those feelings, not to endure them, you see.

68
00:08:13,576 --> 00:08:14,437
And because of that,

69
00:08:14,889 --> 00:08:37,860
we have this the underlying tendency of seeking happiness in in pleasure is reinforced and we keep thinking that the way to happiness is to keep reinforcing this pleasure that we get from worldly things right but there's the danger the danger is that worldly things

70
00:08:39,950 --> 00:08:43,914
They do not understand, as it really is, the origin and passing away.

71
00:08:44,054 --> 00:08:49,761
In other words, anything you get attached to is going to let you down because it's going to change.

72
00:08:50,022 --> 00:08:50,962
It's going to pass away.

73
00:08:51,543 --> 00:09:00,433
Just when you thought you've got the right person, the right job, the right house, the right car, see, you drop dead.

74
00:09:01,755 --> 00:09:04,077
Or worse, it passes away.

75
00:09:04,097 --> 00:09:08,943
So it's a case of recognizing that as soon as we hold on to something,

76
00:09:09,649 --> 00:09:17,899
it has a great potential of creating suffering for us.

77
00:09:17,919 --> 00:09:21,845
And that's the problem with gratifying ourselves in the world of pleasure.

78
00:09:23,187 --> 00:09:24,408
We don't see the danger.

79
00:09:24,908 --> 00:09:30,135
And when the danger comes, we're stuck with the suffering.

80
00:09:30,155 --> 00:09:31,398
They don't see the escape.

81
00:09:35,682 --> 00:09:38,846
And then he says, when a pleasant feeling arises...

82
00:09:39,231 --> 00:10:04,327
they feel attached so this attached means attached to something like for instance I'm attached to my car it's that sort of use of the word when you're attached to somebody you are in some way psychologically connected with them but often in a way which if they disappear or if the car breaks down there's sorrow, lamentation, grief and despair

83
00:10:22,009 --> 00:10:34,644
So, what the Buddha is saying is, it's not necessary for us to get rid of the joys of life, and it's not necessary for us to reject what is painful in life.

84
00:10:34,664 --> 00:10:36,267
Life is full of joy and woe.

85
00:10:37,067 --> 00:10:41,092
All we have to know is how to relate to this stuff.

86
00:10:41,113 --> 00:10:48,321
So when unpleasant thing comes, to actually just accept it, to bear with it, to endure it,

87
00:10:48,789 --> 00:10:53,553
And when pleasant stuff comes, to be careful that we don't form an attachment to it.

88
00:10:53,573 --> 00:10:54,895
Now that's really difficult.

89
00:10:55,015 --> 00:10:58,178
It's one of my sort of regular teachings here around food.

90
00:10:58,619 --> 00:11:04,865
The distinction between enjoying the food and indulging in it is a very fine one.

91
00:11:06,265 --> 00:11:07,386
But you've got to work at it.

92
00:11:07,846 --> 00:11:10,730
Because when we indulge, the suffering comes.

93
00:11:11,831 --> 00:11:18,476
So you have to be very careful that we don't interpret the Buddha's teaching as life-negative.

94
00:11:18,743 --> 00:11:19,464
Far from it.

95
00:11:20,345 --> 00:11:28,356
Once he was fully liberated, he became one of the most sensual beings that there can be.

96
00:11:28,837 --> 00:11:29,198
Why?

97
00:11:29,239 --> 00:11:33,083
Because now he's completely open to the sensual world.

98
00:11:33,905 --> 00:11:36,870
He's not afraid of it and he's not indulging in it.

99
00:11:40,798 --> 00:11:43,322
So now we have the other side of the equation.

100
00:11:44,224 --> 00:11:51,716
Monks, when the instructed noble disciple experiences a painful feeling, they do not sorrow, grieve or lament.

101
00:11:52,236 --> 00:11:55,020
They do not weep beating their breasts and become distraught.

102
00:11:55,763 --> 00:11:59,447
They feel one feeling, a bodily one, not the mental one.

103
00:12:00,409 --> 00:12:03,094
Suppose they were to strike a man with a dart,

104
00:12:03,344 --> 00:12:11,475
but they would not strike him immediately afterwards with a second dart, so that man would feel a feeling caused by one dart only.

105
00:12:11,875 --> 00:12:23,191
So too, when the instructed disciple experiences a painful feeling, they feel one feeling, a bodily feeling, and not the mental one.

106
00:12:23,211 --> 00:12:28,238
While experiencing the same feeling, they harbour no aversion towards it.

107
00:12:28,504 --> 00:12:37,197
And since they harbour no aversion towards painful feeling, the underlying tendency to aversion towards painful feeling does not lie behind this.

108
00:12:38,099 --> 00:12:47,030
So in other words, even the very conditioning within us that causes this resistance and this indulgence is beginning to fade away.

109
00:12:47,672 --> 00:12:56,605
And of course, the liberated person is one that simply can't react like that anymore because that habit has been completely wiped out.

110
00:12:58,913 --> 00:13:03,477
While experiencing painful feeling, they do not seek delight in sensual pleasure.

111
00:13:03,518 --> 00:13:04,258
For what reason?

112
00:13:04,739 --> 00:13:11,505
Because the instructed noble disciple knows of an escape from painful feeling other than sensual pleasure.

113
00:13:12,067 --> 00:13:15,289
And that's what the purpose of Vipassana is.

114
00:13:15,309 --> 00:13:17,172
It's to discover that escape.

115
00:13:18,092 --> 00:13:26,221
Since they do not seek delight in sensual pleasure, the underlying tendency of lust for pleasant feelings does not lie behind this.

116
00:13:26,861 --> 00:13:27,182
So,

117
00:13:27,533 --> 00:13:29,995
That indulgence is not there.

118
00:13:31,758 --> 00:13:40,288
And they understand it as it really is the origin and the passing away, the gratification, the danger and the escape in the case of these feelings.

119
00:13:40,889 --> 00:13:47,398
And since they understand these things, the underlying tendency of ignorance towards neither pleasant nor pleasant,

120
00:13:47,597 --> 00:13:51,323
Neither painful nor pleasant feeling does not lie behind this.

121
00:13:51,684 --> 00:13:58,975
So remember, we tend to ignore those sensations that we do not see as either painful or pleasant.

122
00:14:00,138 --> 00:14:04,926
So when we come to the breath, generally speaking, we find it boring.

123
00:14:04,946 --> 00:14:08,291
And that shows us that we're constantly trying to seek excitement.

124
00:14:09,493 --> 00:14:13,740
Whereas the spiritual life is drawing us towards silence, towards stillness.

125
00:14:18,884 --> 00:14:20,566
And they feel a pleasant feeling.

126
00:14:20,586 --> 00:14:23,570
If they feel a pleasant feeling, they feel it detached.

127
00:14:24,871 --> 00:14:27,595
They're not becoming psychologically dependent on it.

128
00:14:28,115 --> 00:14:31,660
And if they feel a painful feeling, they feel it detached.

129
00:14:31,681 --> 00:14:36,486
And if they feel a neither painful nor pleasant feeling, they feel it detached.

130
00:14:36,506 --> 00:14:44,857
This is called a noble disciple who is detached, who is not actually, the better phrase is non-attached.

131
00:14:45,259 --> 00:14:54,154
Because the word detached tends to give you the feeling of callousness almost, to be detached from people's suffering and all that.

132
00:14:54,456 --> 00:14:57,682
So it's non-attached from birth, aging and death.

133
00:14:58,263 --> 00:15:02,811
Who is non-attached from sorrow, lamentation, pain, dejection and despair.

134
00:15:03,230 --> 00:15:05,394
Who is non-attached from suffering, I say.

135
00:15:05,864 --> 00:15:18,602
This, monks, is the distinction, the disparity, the difference between the instructed noble disciple and the uninstructed worldling, which we are no longer.

136
00:15:20,206 --> 00:15:23,129
I can only hope my words have been of some assistance.

137
00:15:23,548 --> 00:15:27,340
And that the Buddha's Dharma is coming through loud and clear.

138
00:15:28,062 --> 00:15:36,206
May you, by your great efforts, overcome suffering and do not seek escape through indulgence in pleasure.

139
00:15:37,129 --> 00:15:47,379
Sooner rather than later.

